    <h2 id="what">What heliskiing in Iceland is</h2>
    <p>Heliskiing is off-piste skiing and snowboarding where a helicopter — not a chairlift — carries you to the top of the mountain. You are dropped on a summit or high ridge with a small group and a mountain guide, and you ski a long, untracked descent through open Arctic snow before the helicopter collects you for the next run. There are no lift queues, no crowds and no pistes: just fresh lines chosen for the conditions on the day.</p>
    <p>Iceland has quietly become one of the world's finest heliski destinations. What makes it different from the classic ranges of Canada or Alaska is geography: on the <a href="/iceland">Tröllaskagi (Troll) Peninsula</a> in the north of the country the mountains rise straight out of the Arctic Ocean, so many descents finish at the water's edge. You can ski a 1,000-metre-plus run from a snow-covered summit down to a black-sand fjord shoreline — a sea-to-summit experience that only a handful of places on earth can offer.</p>

    <h2 id="where">Where you ski: the Troll Peninsula</h2>
    <p>The heart of Icelandic heliskiing is the Tröllaskagi Peninsula between the fjord towns of Siglufjörður and Ólafsfjörður in North Iceland. Its glacially-carved peaks reach 1,200–1,500 metres and are packed together tightly, which means a helicopter can access an enormous number of runs within a short flight of base. The terrain suits everyone from strong intermediates — long, rolling powder fields and mellow bowls — to experts looking for steeper couloirs and committing lines.</p>
    <p>Your base is the harbour town of Siglufjörður, home to the four-star <a href="/siglo-hotel">Sigló Hótel</a>. Because the mountains begin at the edge of town, the flying time to the first run is short, and on many days you can ski all the way back down to the hotel. Full detail on the region and how to reach it is on our <a href="/iceland">Iceland guide</a> and <a href="/travel-here">Travel Here</a> pages.</p>

    <h2 id="season">The best time to go heliskiing in Iceland</h2>
    <p>The Icelandic heliski season runs from March to mid-June — one of the longest in the world, thanks to the far-northern latitude and the deep Arctic snowpack. The experience changes character through the season:</p>
    <p><strong>Early season (March–April)</strong> brings the most wintry conditions: powder and light backcountry snow, especially at higher elevations and on north-facing slopes. Nights are still dark enough to see the Northern Lights over the fjords.</p>
    <p><strong>Late season (May–June)</strong> delivers Iceland's famous spring corn snow — smooth, forgiving, sun-softened snow that many skiers rate as the most enjoyable of all — often skied late into the evening under the midnight sun. This is the most reliable window for consistent conditions.</p>
    <p>Neither window is "better" in the abstract; they are simply different trips. If you want powder and aurora, come early. If you want long, warm, high-mileage days under endless daylight, come late.</p>

    <h2 id="terrain">The terrain and how much you actually ski</h2>
    <p>A typical heliski day in Iceland delivers around <strong>15,000–25,000 vertical feet</strong> of skiing — roughly seven to fourteen runs, depending on conditions, group speed and the weather. Individual descents commonly run 800–1,300 vertical metres, and the biggest lines finish at the coast. Because the helicopter removes the climb, you ski far more descent in a day than you ever could at a resort or on a ski tour.</p>
    <p>The ceiling is remarkable. On record days, guests have skied as many as <strong>29 runs and 64,000 vertical feet in a single day</strong>. When conditions and daylight allow, you can buy additional vertical and keep skiing — the sport is only limited by snow, weather and your own legs.</p>

    <h2 id="vertical">Why heliskiing is sold by vertical feet, not flight time</h2>
    <p>Icelandic heliskiing is priced by a guaranteed amount of <strong>vertical feet</strong> rather than by helicopter flight time. This matters more than it sounds. It means you are guaranteed a set amount of actual skiing, and decisions the guides make for safety or weather never reduce what you have already paid for. If the helicopter has to reposition, wait out a squall, or take a safer line, you don't lose your skiing — the clock isn't running against you. Vertical is easy to verify, too, with modern GPS ski-tracking apps. It is the fairest and most transparent way the sport is sold, and it is the model used on every <a href="/packages">Viking Heliskiing package</a>.</p>

    <h2 id="safety">Safety and IFMGA-certified guiding</h2>
    <p>Heliskiing is a backcountry activity, and its risks — principally avalanches — are actively managed by professionals to a very high standard. Every group is led by <strong>IFMGA/UIAGM-certified mountain guides</strong>, the highest international qualification in the profession. These guides assess the snowpack and make route decisions every single day, choosing terrain that matches both the conditions and the ability of the group.</p>
    <p>Every guest is equipped with a full set of top-of-the-line BCA avalanche safety equipment — transceiver, shovel, probe and airbag pack — and receives a complete safety briefing before skiing begins. The helicopters are modern, well-maintained AS-350 B3 (Airbus H125) machines flown by experienced, Arctic-trained SENNAIR pilots whose entire focus is on safety, comfort and the quality of the experience. No amount of preparation removes all risk from mountain sport, but Icelandic heliskiing is run to the most rigorous safety standards in the industry.</p>

    <h2 id="who">Who can go, and how fit you need to be</h2>
    <p>You do not need to be an expert or an elite athlete. Heliskiing in Iceland suits <strong>strong intermediate to advanced skiers and snowboarders</strong> who are comfortable off-piste for a full day. If you can confidently link turns on ungroomed snow, you are ready — the guides choose terrain to match the group, from gentle rolling fields for confident intermediates to steeper lines for experts.</p>
    <p>Fitness matters, but not in the way people fear. The helicopter does all the climbing, so a heliski day is often less exhausting than a full day at a resort. Everyday, good general fitness is enough; deep snow and long descents simply reward those in better condition with more runs. Under-18s are welcome with signed parental approval.</p>

    <h2 id="gear">Gear and what to pack</h2>
    <p>The technical equipment is provided. Guests are supplied with K2 freeride skis or a snowboard suited to Arctic powder, and the complete BCA avalanche safety kit. What you should bring is your own <strong>ski or snowboard boots and helmet</strong> — for the best fit and comfort over long days — plus warm layers, quality gloves, sunglasses and high-SPF sun cream (the Arctic spring sun is deceptively strong, especially reflecting off snow). Most guests travel light and pack only personal fit items and clothing.</p>

    <h2 id="stay">Where you stay</h2>
    <p>Trips are based at the four-star <a href="/siglo-hotel">Sigló Hótel</a>, set on the restored herring harbour of Siglufjörður. It combines the feel of a boutique mountain lodge with genuine four-star comfort: waterfront dining at the Sunna restaurant, geothermal hot tubs on the marina where you can soak after a day's skiing, and Northern-Lights views straight from the water's edge in the early season. Because the hotel sits at the foot of the ski terrain, your day starts and ends without long transfers.</p>

    <h2 id="getting">Getting to the Troll Peninsula</h2>
    <p>Reaching Siglufjörður is straightforward. Most guests fly into Keflavík International Airport (Reykjavík) and continue north, or fly directly to Akureyri, the capital of North Iceland, which is about an hour from Siglufjörður by road. We help arrange the final leg so your arrival is seamless. Full route options and transfer details are on our <a href="/travel-here">Travel Here</a> page.</p>

    <h2 id="cost">Cost and what's included</h2>
    <p>Heliskiing is a premium experience, and Icelandic trips are priced by guaranteed vertical feet with the option to buy more when conditions allow. Our <a href="/packages">packages</a> range across 3, 4 and 5-day weeks, with shared, semi-private and fully-private helicopter options. A package brings together everything: IFMGA-certified guiding, helicopter access with SENNAIR pilots, K2 freeride equipment, the full BCA avalanche safety kit, and accommodation at Sigló Hótel with meals. You can see current pricing and day-by-day structure for each option on the <a href="/classic-heliskiing">Classic</a>, <a href="/heli-assisted-touring">Heli-Assisted Touring</a> and <a href="/private-heliskiing">Private</a> package pages.</p>

    <h2 id="compare">Heliskiing vs cat-skiing vs resort skiing</h2>
    <p>All three get you off the beaten piste, but they are very different experiences. <strong>Resort skiing</strong> gives you lifts, groomed runs and easy access, but crowds and tracked-out snow. <strong>Cat-skiing</strong> uses a snowcat to reach backcountry terrain — more affordable and weather-resilient than a helicopter, but slower, with less vertical per day and limited range. <strong>Heliskiing</strong> is the pinnacle: it reaches terrain nothing else can, delivers by far the most vertical per day, and puts you on untouched snow in remote country. In Iceland specifically, the helicopter is what unlocks the sea-to-summit descents that define the region — no other method can access them. For those who want ski touring built in, our <a href="/heli-assisted-touring">Heli-Assisted Touring</a> package combines both worlds.</p>

    <h2 id="lights">Midnight sun and the Northern Lights</h2>
    <p>Iceland's far-northern position gives heliskiing here two experiences found almost nowhere else. In the early season, clear nights over the fjords often bring the <strong>Northern Lights</strong>, visible from the mountains and even from the hot tubs at Sigló Hótel. In the late season, the sun barely sets: from May into June you can ski and fly late into the evening under the <strong>midnight sun</strong>, in full Arctic daylight. It is one of the very few places on earth where heliskiing under the midnight sun is possible.</p>

    <h2 id="book">How to book — and why through an authorised agent</h2>
    <p>Heliski Travel is the authorised booking agent for Viking Heliskiing on the Troll Peninsula. Booking through an agent costs you no more than booking direct, and gives you a single relationship handling every detail — dates, group size, private or shared flights, hotel, transfers and the small things that make a trip run smoothly. From your first message to the helicopter, one team looks after everything, with a reply within 12 hours.</p>
    <p>The best next step is simply to tell us your dates and group size. Read more about the region on our <a href="/iceland">Iceland guide</a>, browse the <a href="/packages">packages</a>, or <a href="/contact">get in touch</a> for a tailored quote.</p>

